Title: Talisman: Debut of X
A high-dimensional sphere spilling out of a high-dimensional cube despite exponentially many constraints
Description: Make a square, split each side into two halves, producing four cells. Put a circle into each cell such that it fills it completely. There is a small gap right in the middle of the square. Put a circle there again such that it touches the other four circles. The central circle is obviously inside the square, right? Yes, but only if the dimension you are in is $D\le9$. Above that, the central cicle actually spills out from the cube, despite the $2^D$ spheres in their cells keeping it in. In this post I present this simple-to-compute yet utterly counter-intuitive result.
